            "id": "4575631",
            "title": "The Kentucky Derby throws a spotlight on if prediction markets should be legal",
            "description": "<html><body><p data-eci=\"true\">The National Thoroughbred Racing Association has publicly warned that prediction markets should not offer bets on the Kentucky Derby or any other horse races in the U.S. The industry group argued that such activity would violate federal law and undermine the regulated pari-mutuel system. </p>\n<p>In comments filed with the Commodity Futures Trading Commission, National Thoroughbred Racing Association CEO Tom Rooney stressed that wagering on horse racing is governed by the Interstate Horseracing Act of 1978, not by the federal commodities laws that the CFTC uses to authorize prediction-market event contracts.</p>\n<p>The NTRA maintains that any contract based on the outcome of a horse race that bypasses the Interstate Horseracing Act would conflict with the statute and with the public interest and therefore falls outside what the CFTC should permit. He emphasized that the IHA requires explicit consent from entities such as the host track or racing commission before outside wagering-style products can be tied to a race and that no such consent has been granted to any prediction-market operator. </p>\n<p>It was also highlighted that if prediction markets such as Polymarket (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/POLYMARKET\" title=\"Polymarket Inc.\">POLYMARKET</a>) and Kalshi (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/KALSHI\" title=\"Kalshi Inc\">KALSHI</a>) were allowed to take Derby-related bets, they could divert substantial betting revenue away from the traditional pari-mutuel system on which racetracks, horsemen, and state tax streams depend. </p>\n<p>A clear beneficiary of the Kentucky Derby is Churchill Downs Incorporated (<span class=\"ticker-hover-wrapper\"><span class=\"ticker-hover-wrapper\"><a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/CHDN\" title=\"Churchill Downs Incorporated\">CHDN</a></span></span>), which owns the Churchill Downs track, operates the Derby, and also benefits from wagering, media, hospitality, and related gaming activity around race day. Last year, t<span>otal Derby Day wagering reached $349.0M, and total Derby Week handle hit $473.9M, both all-time highs.</span></p>\n<p>DraftKings (<span class=\"ticker-hover-wrapper\"><span class=\"ticker-hover-wrapper\"><a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/DKNG\" title=\"DraftKings Inc.\">DKNG</a></span></span>), FanDuel (<span class=\"ticker-hover-wrapper\"><span class=\"ticker-hover-wrapper\"><a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/FLUT\" title=\"Flutter Entertainment plc\">FLUT</a></span></span>), and BetMGM (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/MGM\" title=\"MGM Resorts International\">MGM</a>) (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/GMVHF\" title=\"Entain Plc\">GMVHF</a>) are also interested in keeping prediction markets away from the Kentucky Derby and other major horse races.</p>\n<p>The Kentucky Derby is set for May 2. Derby Week at Churchill Downs begins on April 25.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<div class=\"signup_widget_placeholder\"></div>\n</body></html>",
            "image": "https://static.seekingalpha.com/assets/og_image_1200-29b2bfe1a595477db6826bd2126c63ac2091efb7ec76347a8e7f81ba17e3de6c.png",
            "link": "https://seekingalpha.com/news/4575631-the-kentucky-derby-throws-a-spotlight-on-if-prediction-markets-should-be-legal",
            "pub_date": "2026-04-16 19:09:36",
            "source": "seekalpha",
            "kind": 1,
            "language": "en"
        },
